title: For Sale:  Lee Enfield Jungle Carbine 303 British
postcontent: Jungle Carbine was an informal term used for the Rifle No. 5 Mk I[2] which was a derivative of the British Lee Enfield No. 4 Mk I, designed not for jungle fighting but in response to a requirement for a "Shortened, Lightened" version of the No.4 rifle for airborne forces in the European theatre of operations. The end of the war in Europe overtook widespread issue of the No.5 and most of the operational use of this rifle occurred in post-war colonial campaigns such as the Malayan emergency, where engagement ranges tended to be shorter and its handier size and reduced weight were an advantage. This is where the "Jungle Carbine" nickname comes from. Production began in March 1944, and finished in December 1947.  This one is Dated June 1944 and has always been a great shooter.

title: For Sale:  WARNING
postcontent:
I posted a WTB ad and was contacted by the same person twice, first from a Washington DC area code, then from a North Carolina area code claiming to have the gun I was looking for. 
 I was suspicious about the two phone numbers, and then he gave me the usual B.S. story that panhandlers often give about his dad being in the hospital and he's selling it to pay his dad's hospital bills (major red flag) and on top of that he talked with very broken English, so I did a little research on those area codes and a lot of scams come from those area codes. The people calling are actually in places like India, Jamaica, Taiwan, Somalia, etc. but their calls are somehow routed through those area codes. First he said he was in California, but then he wanted me to send a money order to North Carolina. I didn't.
 So just a heads up to everyone, the same people who do telephone scams are now targeting Armslist users so be very cautious who you buy from, ask lots of questions, and use some common sense when dealing with people and your money.

title: Want To Buy:  SCAM WARNING!
postcontent:
I had a WTB ad for a Gen 1 Glock 17 and was contacted by the same person twice, first from a Washington DC area Code, and then from a North Carolina area code. He first claimed to be in California, but wanted me to send a money order to "his family in North Carolina" (I didn't) He then went on to give me the usual B.S. story panhandlers often use about his dad being in the hospital and he needed the money to pay his father's medical bills (red flag!) And he also used very Broken English. He used a Spanish name, I think these scammers have figured out that their English is broken so they pretend to be Mexican in hopes that that will explain away their broken English.
 Well, I did a little research on those area codes and a quick Google search said that said that a lot of scam calls AND TEXTS come from those area codes. Often the callers are actually in somewhere like Somalia, India, Taiwan, Jamaica, etc. but they somehow route their calls through US area codes. So these scammers aren't just calling random people anymore, they're also searching ads and targeting people who want to buy things. So just a heads up to everyone, be careful about who you do business with, ask lots of questions, and just use common sense when dealing with people and YOUR money!
